type: call, flight call, male, nocturnal flight call, song
rmk:
Another recording of the so called 'Terminal Phase' type of NJ song type, cf. [Docker 2020] I described this type "Standby mode churring"  because it is lower in frequency and intesity initially as "Weiterrollen" ("continued rolling"). Position 1min 54 sec. 
Recorded with my stereo parabolic reflector microphone from wildtronics.com #WTPMMSA on LS-11 (OLYMPUS) SD recording device. Dish mounted on tripod. Distance approx. 150m. 
Recorded during 2nd Austrian Night of The Nightjar event (all night on site monitoring). 
No filtering applied. 

[Docker 2020] Docker, S., Lowe, A. & Abrahams, C. Identification of different song types in the European Nightjar Caprimulgus europaeus. Bird Study 67, 119–127; 10.1080/00063657.2020.1780414 (2020).

Churring from a singing Nightjar for a constant five minutes. Listen carefully at the end of the recording and you can hear the wing beats of the bird flying off from its perch at the top of a tree. 
The habitat here is conifer plantation at the boundary of mature trees and a rough area that had previously been cleared. Recorded on a beautiful, clear and warm evening with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 on a tripod.
Some editing of EQ around 450 Hz to reduce the sound from farm machinery and also some reduction of barking dogs below 800 Hz.

I also made two other recordings of Nightjars this evening:

XC484859

XC484860

My first recording of the so called 'Terminal Phase' type of NJ, cf. [Docker 2020] I described this type "Standby mode churring",  because it is lower in frequency and intensity initially in German as "Weiterrollen" ("continued rolling").
Recorded with my stereo parabolic reflector microphone from wildtronics.com #WTPMMSA on LS-11 (OLYMPUS) SD recording device. Dish mounted on tripod. Distance approx. 150m. 
Recorded during "First Austrian Night of The Nightjar" event (all night on site monitoring). 
No filtering applied. 

[Docker 2020] Docker, S., Lowe, A. & Abrahams, C. Identification of different song types in the European Nightjar Caprimulgus europaeus. Bird Study 67, 119–127; 10.1080/00063657.2020.1780414 (2020).

Subset of churring Nightjar recorded with my stereo parabolic reflector microphone from wildtronics.com #WTPMMSA on LS-11 (OLYMPUS) SD recording device. Dish mounted on tripod.

Recording made at the edge of a clearfelling.
Video shows female starting to walk, rather fast without the usual shiffering.
Temperature has risen to 52 Celsius, so she is leading the two chicks to a cooler place at the other side of a heap of dead branches. 
Second bird in the background is making the same call, this second bird could be the male.
Not a common sound.
It sounds like the contact-call adults utters to call the chicks before feeding, but it is much louder and more agitated.
